      <div id="mainContent" class="main column clearfix"> 
       <h1>Reagan, Gorbachev Share Radical Vision</h1>
       <div class="alignRight newsimagelarge">
        <img src="/uploadedImages/_VMI/Communications_Marketing/Newscenter/Headlines/Headline_Images/13-14/ReaganConfPan52015krr_0042Fulltext.jpg" alt="FullTextImage/img/@alt" class="bordered">
        <span class="caption">Beth Fischer addresses conference participants in the final panel of the "Enduring Legacy" conference. – VMI Photo by Kevin Remington.</span>
       </div>
       <p class="sub-header-italic">Final Panel Closes Reagan Legacy Conference</p>
       <p>LEXINGTON, Va., Nov. 4, 2014 – “The Enduring Legacy: Leadership and National Security Affairs During the Ronald Reagan Era” came to a close today with a panel session that gave insight into the motivations of the two world leaders whose ideals and efforts made possible a peaceful end to the Cold War: President Ronald Reagan and Soviet General Secretary Mikhail Gorbachev.<br><br>Beth Fischer, a lecturer at the University of Toronto, spoke about Reagan’s desire to eradicate nuclear weapons, a vision that informed his foreign policies across the board and allowed him to establish a meaningful dialogue with Gorbachev.<br><br>“In his view, nuclear weapons and mutually assured destruction were morally reprehensible,” Fischer. “He sought to fundamentally change the way we think about nuclear weapons and American security.”<br><br>This was a radical vision for the time, one that was opposed by Reagan’s advisers, fellow conservatives, and allies across the world.<br><br>“There was only one leader in the whole world who also wanted to eliminate nuclear weapons, and that happened to be Mikhail Gorbachev,” said Fischer. “On this one issue, eradicating nuclear weapons, they saw eye to eye. … This was the foundation for the peaceful resolution of the Cold War.”<br><br>Fischer dismissed what she calls the myth of triumphalism, the idea that the American military buildup and demonstrations of resolve led to the eventual collapse of the Soviet Union. Rather, Fischer sees the peaceful resolution of the Cold War as a result of successful diplomacy.<br><br>“Remarkably, the president was able to put aside his own convictions about communism at the height of the Cold War to pursue a more secure, more humane world,” said Fischer. “President Reagan hated communism, but he hated nuclear weapons even more.”<br><br>Emeritus Professor of Politics at Oxford University Archie Brown provided a portrait of Gorbachev within the Soviet political system.<br><br>“Behind the monolithic facade that the communist party of the Soviet Union presented to its own people and to the outside world, there was a wide variety of views,” said Brown. <br><br>Under Gorbachev, the articulation of diverse views within the regime was encouraged, allowing for an open exchange of ideas. Likewise, perestroika and glasnost reforms rapidly changed the political and social terrain of the USSR.<br><br>“Before Gorbachev’s reforms, if you were caught with a copy of George Orwell’s 1984 or Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn’s Gulag Archipelago, you could expect a trip to the gulag yourself,” said Brown, noting that by 1988 huge editions of such books were printed in Moscow.<br><br>These domestic reforms had powerful reverberations in Soviet foreign policy.<br><br>“As the Soviet system became freer by the month, this vastly improved the atmosphere in which meetings with western leaders took place,” said Brown. “In foreign policy, the most fundamental change that Gorbachev made was encapsulated in his declaration, ‘The people of every county have a right to decide for themselves what kind of political and economic system they wish to live in.’”<br><br>This re-evaluation of foreign and domestic policies removed the ideological foundation for the Cold War, allowing it to come to a peaceful close.<br><br>“The fact that Reagan and Gorbachev were thinking about ending the Cold War was huge. It was radical,” said Fischer. “Most people thought if the Cold War was ever to end, it would end in nuclear Armageddon. No one imagined that it would end peacefully.”<br><br>Looking back to the challenges of the Cold War is vital to the mission of the John A. Adams ’71 Center for Military History and Strategic Analysis, which, with the Center for Leadership and Ethics, sponsored the conference.<br><br>“The Reagan period is so important,” said Lt. Col. Brad Coleman ’95, associate professor of history, noting that the center’s focus is on “how the Cold War shapes the challenges and opportunities we face today.” The Reagan conference was the first major conference on the VMI post sponsored by the Adams Center.<br><br>On the horizon for the Adams Center are an applied history conference and a George C. Marshall conference, both looking to glean insight from history relevant to current affairs and bring cadets together with scholars, national security professionals, and fellow students.<br><br>“Ultimately, my vision for the Adams Center is that it becomes a platform for collaboration, not only across disciplines and departments here at VMI but also across the community more broadly,” said Coleman.<br><br><em>-John Robertson IV</em></p>
       <p align="center">-VMI-</p> 
